%I A396950 #15 Jun 16 2026 18:35:38
%S A396950 1,2,3,4,7,14,13,26,51,50,106,148,147,146,362,361,456,541,652,651,902,
%T A396950 1028,1237,1236,1808,2053,2115,2114,2113,3466,3609,3708,3707,3706,
%U A396950 4953,4952,4951,6007,6192,6191,6190,6189,6946,6945,12017,12016,12015,12014,12187
%N A396950 a(n) is the smallest integer m such that A396377(m) = n.
%C A396950 After problem proposed by Paul Erdős (see link).
%H A396950 David A. Corneth, <a href="/A396950/b396950.txt">Table of n, a(n) for n = 1..431</a> (terms <= 10^8)
%H A396950 Paul Erdős, <a href="https://combinatorica.hu/~p_erdos/1963-14.pdf">Quelques problèmes de Théorie des Nombres</a>, Monographies de l'Enseignement Mathématique, No. 6, pp. 81-135, L'Enseignement Mathématique, Université, Geneva, 1963, problem 15, p. 90.
%F A396950 a(n) = min{k >= 1 : A396377(k) = n}.
%e A396950 a(6) = 14 because A396377(14) = 6 and in the set {14, 15, 16, 17, 18, 19, 20}, we have 16 | 14 * 15 * 17 * 18 * 19 * 20 and there is no m < 14 that needs a set of exactly 7 integers {m, m+1, ..., m+6} to get an integer who divides the product of the other integers.
%Y A396950 Cf. A396377, A396378, A396379, A396380.
%K A396950 nonn,new
%O A396950 1,2
%A A396950 _Bernard Schott_, Jun 11 2026
